    <div style="font-size:96px;font-weight:900;color:var(--accent);letter-spacing:-2.5px;line-height:0.95;margin:6px 0 6px;">WHO</div>
    <h1 class="h-title">Governance &middot; who is accountable</h1>
    <div class="h-subtitle">Decision rights, accountability, escalation</div>
    <p class="h-intro">The other three frames describe what the operating model is, when it runs and how it operates. This frame is what makes it a thing people own rather than a thing people describe. Names against each part of the operating model. Decision rights for changes. Escalation routes when configurations conflict. Without this layer the operating model is a beautiful piece of architecture nobody is responsible for.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="status-banner">
    <div class="status-banner-h">Roles populated, named accountability still to land</div>
    <div class="status-banner-body">This frame uses <strong>roles, not named individuals</strong>. It describes who is accountable, responsible, consulted and informed once the operating model is live and running, the end-state RACI. Roles are deliberately not named to individuals on this page; that is the SRO's call once the model is signed off. The architectural RACI rows still show TBC where the end-state owner has not yet been agreed.</div>
  </div>

  <details class="gov-q-banner" id="open-q">
    <summary>
      <span><span class="gov-q-h">Key open governance questions</span><span class="gov-q-count">10 items</span></span>
    </summary>
    <div class="gov-q-body">
      Ten things SLT needs to land before this skeleton becomes named accountability. The TBC cells across the architectural RACI and the configuration-specific tables are pointing at these: making them explicit here.
      <ul style="margin:10px 0 0 22px; padding:0; font-size:12.5px; line-height:1.6;">
        <li><strong>Permanent platform hosting post-Beta.</strong> Architectural RACI for the Foundation is TBC. When HomeTest exits discovery, where does the platform live permanently: inside NHSE, an ALB, or a new entity? <em>Owner: SRO with Commercial Operations and NHSE Commercial.</em></li>
        <li><strong>Procurement vehicle: three-step decision shape.</strong> Three steps land in sequence. <strong>Step 1 (interim route to market)</strong>: six-month SBS PSR bridge for the HIV use case only; Alpha/Beta MOUs continue to cover live deployments. <strong>Step 2 (steady-state procurement vehicle)</strong>: PA23 is the recommended procurement regime per the Recommendation paper, supported by NHS Legal (formal advice note follows the recommendation rather than gates it). Working dual-route: Plan A , PA23 Dynamic Market (working position following the external procurement legal counsel workshop on 18 June; Open Framework remains on the table); Plan B , Digital Primary Care framework leverage; Plan C , commissioner-led direct purchase. <strong>Step 3 (framework administration route)</strong>: NHSE direct, SBS, CCS or third-party; coupled to Step 2. SLT alignment at the 22 June Leeds playback. Originally targeted April 2027 framework standup has been retired as a current planning commitment. <em>Owner: Commercial Operations with NHSE Commercial and NHS Legal.</em></li>
        <li><strong>Aisha's accountability split across initiation patterns.</strong> The two configuration RACIs below split clinical accountability differently: Sex Health Service Clinical Lead in HIV, Acute Trust Consultant and Clinical Safety Officer in PSA. <strong>Now clarified:</strong> Aisha represents the deployer-side CSO archetype; the platform-side (manufacturer) CSO is a separate appointment. Both must be independent to remove conflict of interest. Overarching accountability across both pathways still needs an explicit single statement at the deployer-side level. <em>Owner: Clinical Safety Group.</em></li>
        <li><strong>National Assurance Board composition and constitutional layer.</strong> Who sits on it? Who owns final authority? How are disputes arbitrated? What is the appeals process? How are standards updated? How are suppliers challenged? Currently a name in the architecture, not a constituted body. <em>Owner: SRO with NHSE, Clinical Safety Group input.</em></li>
        <li><strong>National orchestration BAU funding.</strong> Who funds the routing, DevOps, interoperability, assurance management, Blue Book maintenance, supplier onboarding, analytics and standards updates at steady state? The percent-fee-per-transaction model covers the platform foundation but the BAU team and its likely cost have not been sized. <em>Owner: Commercial Operations with NHSE Commercial and Health Economist.</em></li>
        <li><strong>Adoption as a named function in the model.</strong> Adoption activity is being delivered through the Partnerships workstream. The unresolved question is whether adoption should be surfaced structurally in the operating model itself (an overlay, a foundation capability, a row in the RACI) or stay implicit inside Partnerships. <em>Decision: SLT to confirm.</em></li>
        <li><strong>National rollout without local fragmentation.</strong> The architecture answers what the model is composed of. It does not yet answer how the model gets rolled out at national scale so that LAs, ICBs and Trusts adopt it consistently rather than each diverging from the agreed pattern. This is execution discipline (sequencing, priorities, governance of variation), not architecture. <em>Owner: SRO with Commercial Operations and NHSE Commercial.</em></li>
        <li><strong>Data controller framework.</strong> The federated multi-controller model has NHSE as controller for the foundation, commissioner as controller for the testing purpose, and supplier as processor. Joint-controller arrangements have been ruled out. The exact controller designation per configuration is still being scoped, and the lawful basis position (direct consent vs legal directions) is unresolved at SLT level. Affects every DPIA, every DSA and every supplier contract. <em>Decision: SLT with NHS Legal and Caldicott Guardian.</em></li>
        <li><strong>IAO appointed.</strong> NHSE policy requires the Information Asset Owner to be a permanent NHSE employee. The role is now filled and the IG lead confirmed the issue solved at the June 2026 Delivery Board; the risk register is being downgraded accordingly. Formal sign-off to process live patient data is no longer blocked on this item; remaining IG sign-off tracks through the DPIA. <em>Closed June 2026. Owner: SRO.</em></li>
        <li><strong>Cost-benefit dislocation at local system level.</strong> Home testing replaces venepuncture, but the saving and the new spend land in different parts of the local budget. Pathology networks don't run phlebotomy; phlebotomy sits in clinical services or under the ICB. Without best-practice tariffs at pathway level, ICBs see home testing as a cost pressure rather than a value case, even when the whole-pathway economics are positive. The economic case is the unlock for adoption. <em>Decision: SLT with NHSE strategic finance and Health Economist input.</em></li>
      </ul>
